{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17524191","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17524191"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:02:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:02:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13979"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13979","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13979"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.01,0.81,0.02,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6613"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112704"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6613","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6613"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13979"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94737"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2637"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13379"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14090"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29609"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46319"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112704","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112704"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 54-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a swelling across his left elbow. He has had it for the last three weeks. He denies any direct trauma or recent surgery over the area. The swelling has slightly increased in size over the weeks and is now causing him some discomfort. His only medical history is hypertension. He takes antihypertensive medications only. He is a non-smoker and drinks two standard drinks per week. He works as a plumber. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The picture below shows the appearance of his left elbow (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gouty arthritis","Septic arthritis","Olecranon bursitis","Triceps tendinitis","Lipoma"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOlecranon bursitis\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis in this case. It typically presents as a fluctuant swelling over the posterior aspect of the elbow, which is consistent with the image provided. The swelling can be associated with varying degrees of pain. The gradual onset over three weeks and the patient\u0027s occupation as a plumber, which likely involves repetitive pressure on the elbow, support this diagnosis. Olecranon bursitis can be caused by repetitive microtrauma, infection, or systemic conditions like gout or rheumatoid arthritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGouty arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with sudden onset of severe pain, redness, and swelling, often affecting the first metatarsophalangeal joint. While it can affect the elbow, the gradual onset and lack of significant pain make this diagnosis less likely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeptic arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E is an emergency condition characterised by acute onset of joint pain, swelling, warmth, and often fever. The patient\u0027s afebrile state, gradual onset, and lack of significant pain make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETriceps tendinitis\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents with pain and tenderness at the back of the elbow, particularly with extension against resistance. The prominent swelling seen in the image is not typical of tendinitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELipoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a benign soft tissue tumour that can occur anywhere in the body. While it can present as a painless swelling, lipomas are typically soft and mobile, not fluctuant like the swelling seen in olecranon bursitis. The location and appearance are more consistent with olecranon bursitis than a lipoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn conclusion, the patient\u0027s presentation of a gradually enlarging, swelling with minimal pain over the olecranon process, combined with his occupation as a plumber (which may involve repetitive pressure on the elbow), strongly suggests olecranon bursitis as the most likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Olecranon bursitis typically presents as a tender swelling over the posterior elbow.","Occupations involving repetitive elbow pressure or microtrauma are risk factors for olecranon bursitis.","Absence of fever and gradual onset help differentiate olecranon bursitis from septic bursitis or arthritis."],"references":["Olecranon bursitis, Orthobullets. https://step2.medbullets.com/orthopedics/120508/olecranon-bursitis","Olecranon bursitis. StatPearls. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470291/#:~:text=Differential%20Diagnosis\u0026text=Among%20other%20diagnoses%2C%20one%20might,%2C%20neoplasm%2C%20or%20ligament%20rupture."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94737"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13979"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20872"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20872","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20872"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/GwieMIho05qvJKz38fKaI2XdNdKsRL.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/GwieMIho05qvJKz38fKaI2XdNdKsRL.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1125}},{"t